Corena Debassige, rRenee Masching, and rWanda Whitebird -- tEmerging paradigms for managing conflicts through applied arts /rKennedy C. Chinyowa -- tCorroding the comforts of social work knowing : persons with intellectual disabilities claim the right of inspection over public photographic images /rAnn Fudge Schormans -- tBringing relating to the forefront : using the art of improvisation to actively perceive relational processes actively in social work /rCathy Paton -- tMaking meaning of our experiences of bearing witness to suffering : employing A/R/Tography to surface co-remembrance and (dwelling) place /rPatti McGillicuddy, rNadine Cross, rGail Mitchell, rNAncy Davis Halifax, and rCarolyn Plummer.  a"The past two decades have witnessed a vigorous challenge to social work. A growing global convergence between the market and the public sector means that private sector values, priorities, and forms of work organization increasingly permeate social and community services. As challenges facing people and communities become more layered and complex, our means of responding become more time-bound and reductionist. This book is premised on the belief in the revitalizing power of arts-informed approaches to social justice work; it affirms and invites creative responses to personal, community, and political struggles and aspirations. The projects described in the book address themes of colonization, displacement and forced migration, sexual violence, ableism, and vicarious trauma. Each chapter shows how art can facilitate transformation: by supporting processes of conscientization and enabling re-storying of selves and identities; by contributing to community and cultural healing, sustainability and resilience; by helping us understand and challenge oppressive social relations; and by deepening experiences, images, and practices of care." -- Publisher's description.  aIssued also in electronic format.  a8 28 29 43 0aArts and societyzCanada. 0aArts